> Rhys, Dominik - rather than me handing you the data it may be better for you to download it from the original
> source:
>
> http://www2.statsghana.gov.gh/nada/index.php/catalog/97/study-description
>
> You will need to register for an account; once you have done this, click on the 'Get Microdata' tab and download
> one or other of the files. Which one you choose will depend on the format you want - the top one is in Stata format
> and the bottom is SPSS format.
>
> Once you've unpacked the data file you will have four subdirectories - aggregates, community, PartAB, and price.
> The most relevant one is PartAB. Unless you want to work in Stata or SPSS you will need to change the format into
> one you can use with your favourite data analysis software (e.g. Matlab, R, Python). I use R, which has tools to
> convert SPSS files to CSV. I imagine Matlab, Python etc. have similar tools. 
>
> From the same website you should also download the documentation file from the Documentation tab - 'GLSS 7
> Questionnaire and Manual'. This is rather misleading because it isn't really documentation but rather the
> questionnaires which were used to collect the data. Anyway, the parts of the questionnaire relating to the data in
> the PartAB subdirectory are contained in the files 'GLSS7_MODULE_A_30_09_16_for print.docx' and
> 'GLSS7_MODULE_B_14_10_16.docx'.
>
> The data which is most obviously relevant to water quality/water security is contained in Module A, Section 7, Part D
> (Utilities and amenities); see page 73 of GLSS7_MODULE_A...docx. The data for this section is in the file
> PartAB/PartA/g7sec7.sav (if using SPSS format). Once you've converted this e.g. to CSV format, you will see that
> the column names refer to the questions. So, the answer to Module A, Section 7, Part D, q1a, Drinking, is stored in
> the column named s7dq1a1; the answer to to Module A, Section 7, Part D, q1a, General use, is stored under
> column s7dq1a, and so on. It's a bit ambiguous in places but should be mostly tractable. 
>
> If Mike agrees, I suggest you work on the above and get a feel for the data. If you have any questions or problems
> then please let me know. I'm in college all week so can help if needed.
>
> Cheers,
> Simon
